# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blockchain-sharding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Several Layer 2 solutions have been implemented as a result.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network allows near-instant, low-fee payments that settle on the Bitcoin base layer.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] The Liquid Network is a sidechain built on top of Bitcoin which processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] The block size limit, in concert with the proof-of-work difficulty adjustment settings of bitcoin's consensus protocol, constitutes a bottleneck in bitcoin's transaction processing capacity.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] This can result in increasing transaction fees and delayed processing of transactions that cannot be fit into a block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Various proposals have come forth on how to scale bitcoin, and a contentious debate has resulted.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Technical optimizations may decrease the amount of computing resources required to receive, process and record bitcoin transactions, allowing increased throughput without placing extra demand on the bitcoin network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] These modifications can be to either the network, in which case a fork is required, or to individual node software (such as Bitcoin Core).
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network (LN) is a protocol that aims to improve bitcoin's scalability and speed without sacrificing trustless operation.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network requires putting a funding transaction on the blockchain to open a payment channel.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Once a channel is opened, connected participants are able to make rapid payments within the channel or may route payments by "hopping" between channels at intermediate nodes for little to no fee.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] In January 2018 Blockstream launched a payment processing system for web retailers called "Lightning Charge", noted that lightning was live on mainnet with 200 nodes operating as of 27 January 2018 and advised it should still be considered "in testing".
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] The Liquid Network is a sidechain that Blockstream developed which is built on top of Bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] It processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] On 15 March 2018, Lightning Labs released the beta version of its lnd Lightning Network implementation for bitcoin mainnet, and on 28 March 2018, ACINQ released a mainnet beta of its eclair implementation and desktop application.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] In January 2019 the online retailer Bitrefill announced that it receives more payments in Bitcoin via the lightning network than any other cryptocurrency they accept.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] In June 2021, the Legislative Assembly of El Salvador voted legislation to make Bitcoin legal tender in El Salvador.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] The decision was based on the success of the Bitcoin Beach ecosystem in El Zonte that used a LN based wallet.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] The government will be introducing a wallet utilising the Lightning Network protocol while giving the freedom for citizens to use other Bitcoin Lightning wallets.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] In 2025, El Salvador's bitcoin project was discontinued as a whole.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin has a block time of 10 minutes and a block size of 1 MB.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Various increases to this limit, and proposals to remove it completely, have been proposed over bitcoin's history.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Implementing any of these proposals involves a fork.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Litecoin produces blocks four times faster than Bitcoin which leads to a 4x improvement in throughput.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Dogecoin has even more throughput with a block time of 1 minute.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin Cash has a block size of 32 MB and hence 32x more throughput than Bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-sharding/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin SV removed the block size limit altogether.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] "Don't trust, verify" is a common maxim in Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The idea is that your node can independently verify that the information it receives is correct by executing all the transactions in the blocks they receive from peers to ensure that the changes proposed precisely match those computed independently by the node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This means nodes do not have to trust that the senders of the block are honest.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This is not possible if data is missing.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] You should have a good understanding of blockchain fundamentals, especially consensus mechanisms.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This page also assumes the reader is familiar with blocks, transactions, nodes, scaling solutions, and other relevant topics.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The data availability problem is the need to prove to the whole network that the summarized form of some transaction data that is being added to the blockchain really represents a set of valid transactions, but doing so without requiring all nodes to download all data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The full transaction data is necessary for independently verifying blocks, but requiring all nodes to download all transaction data is a barrier to scaling.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Solutions to the data availability problem aim to provide sufficient assurances that the full transaction data was made available for verification to network participants that do not download and store the data for themselves.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Light nodes and Layer 2 rollups are important examples of network participants that require strong data availability assurances but cannot download and process transaction data for themselves.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Avoiding downloading transaction data is what makes light nodes light and enables rollups to be effective scaling solutions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Data availability is also a critical concern for future "stateless" Ethereum clients that do not need to download and store state data in order to verify blocks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The stateless clients still need to be certain that the data is available *somewhere* and that it has been processed correctly.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Data Availability Sampling (DAS) is a way for the network to check that data is available without putting too much strain on any individual node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Each node (including non-staking nodes) downloads some small, randomly selected subset of the total data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Successfully downloading the samples confirms with high confidence that all of the data is available.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This relies upon data erasure coding, which expands a given dataset with redundant information (the way this is done is to fit a function known as a *polynomial* over the data and evaluating that polynomial at additional points).
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This allows the original data to be recovered from the redundant data when necessary.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] A consequence of this data creation is that if *any* of the original data is unavailable, *half* of the expanded data will be missing!
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The amount of data samples downloaded by each node can be tuned so that it is *extremely* likely that at least one of the data fragments sampled by each client will be missing *if* less than half the data is really available.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] DAS will be used to ensure rollup operators make their transaction data available after Full Danksharding has been implemented.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Ethereum nodes will randomly sample the transaction data provided in blobs using the redundancy scheme explained above to ensure that all the data exists.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The same technique could also be employed to ensure block producers are making all their data available to secure light clients.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Similarly, under proposer-builder separation, only the block builder would be required to process an entire block - other validators would verify using data availability sampling.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Data Availability Committees (DACs) are trusted parties that provide, or attest to, data availability.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] DACs can be used instead of, or in combination with (opens in a new tab) DAS.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The security guarantees that come with committees depends on the specific set up.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Ethereum uses randomly sampled subsets of validators to attest to data availability for light nodes, for example.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The DAC is a trusted set of nodes that stores copies of data offline.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The DAC is required to make the data available in the event of a dispute.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Members of the DAC also publish onchain attestations to prove that the said data is indeed available.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Some validiums replace DACs with a proof-of-stake (PoS) validator system.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Here, anyone can become a validator and store data offchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] However, they must provide a “bond”, which is deposited in a smart contract.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] In the event of malicious behavior, such as the validator withholding data, the bond can be slashed.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Proof-of-stake data availability committees are considerably more secure than regular DACs because they directly incentivize honest behavior.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Light nodes need to validate the correctness of the block headers they receive without downloading the block data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The cost of this lightness is the inability to independently verify the block headers by re-executing transactions locally in the way full nodes do.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Ethereum light nodes trust random sets of 512 validators that have been assigned to a *sync committee*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The sync committee acts as a DAC that signals to light clients that the data in the header is correct using a cryptographic signature.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Every day, the sync committee refreshes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Each block header alerts light nodes as to which validators to expect to sign off the *next* block, so they can't be tricked into trusting a malicious group pretending to be the real sync-committee.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] However, what happens if an attacker somehow *does* manage to pass a malicious block header to light clients and convince them that it was signed off by an honest sync-committee?
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] In that case, the attacker could include invalid transactions and the light client would blindly accept them, as they do not independently check all the state changes summarized in the block header.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] To protect against this, the light client could use fraud proofs.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Light nodes could pick up those fraud-proofs and use them to discard bad block headers, ensuring they stay on the same honest chain as the full nodes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This relies on full nodes having access to full transaction data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] An attacker who broadcasts a bad block header and also fails to make the transaction data available would be able to prevent full nodes from generating fraud proofs.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The full nodes might be able to signal a warning about a bad block, but they couldn't back up their warning with proof, because the data wasn't made available to generate the proof from!
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The solution to this data availability problem is DAS.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Light nodes download very small random chunks of the full state data and use the samples to verify that the full data set is available.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The actual likelihood of incorrectly assuming full data availability after downloading N random chunks can be calculated (for 100 chunks the chance is 10^-30 (opens in a new tab), i.e., incredibly unlikely).
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Even in this scenario, attacks that withhold just a few bytes could feasibly go unnoticed by clients making random data requests.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Erasure coding fixes this by reconstructing small missing pieces of data that can be used to check proposed state changes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] A fraud proof could then be constructed using the reconstructed data, preventing light nodes from accepting bad headers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Layer 2 scaling solutions, such as , reduce transaction costs and increase Ethereum's throughput by processing transactions offchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Rollup transactions are compressed and posted on Ethereum in batches.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Batches represent thousands of individual offchain transactions in a single transaction on Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This reduces congestion on the base layer and reduces fees for users.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] However, it is only possible to trust the 'summary' transactions posted to Ethereum if the state change proposed can be independently verified and confirmed to be the result of applying all the individual offchain transactions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] If rollup operators do not make the transaction data available for this verification, then they could send incorrect data to Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Optimistic rollups post compressed transaction data to Ethereum and wait for some amount of time (typically 7 days) to allow independent verifiers to check the data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] If anyone identifies a problem, they can generate a fraud-proof and use it to challenge the rollup.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This would cause the chain to roll back and omit the invalid block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This is only possible if data is available.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Currently, there are two ways that optimistic rollups post transaction data to L1.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Some rollups make data permanently available as `CALLDATA` which lives permanently onchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] With the implementation of EIP-4844, some rollups post their transaction data to cheaper blob storage instead.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Independent verifiers have to query the blobs and raise their challenges within ~18 days before the data is deleted from Ethereum layer-1.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Data availability is only guaranteed by the Ethereum protocol for that short fixed window.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] After that, it becomes the responsibility of other entities in the Ethereum ecosystem.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Any node can verify data availability using DAS, i.e., by downloading small, random samples of the blob data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Zero-knowledge (ZK) rollups don't need to post transaction data since guarantee the correctness of state transitions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] However, data availability is still an issue because we can't guarantee the functionality of the ZK-rollup (or interact with it) without access to its state data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] For example, users cannot know their balances if an operator withholds details about the rollup’s state.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Also, they cannot perform state updates using information contained in a newly added block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Data availability is different from data retrievability.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Data availability is the assurance that full nodes have been able to access and verify the full set of transactions associated with a specific block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] It does not necessarily follow that the data is accessible forever.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Data retrievability is the ability of nodes to retrieve *historical information* from the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] This historical data is not needed for verifying new blocks, it is only required for syncing full nodes from the genesis block or serving specific historical requests.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] The core Ethereum protocol is primarily concerned with data availability, not data retrievability.
[src:blockchain-sharding/data-availability] Data retrievability can be provided by a small population of archive nodes run by third parties, or it can be distributed across the network using decentralized file storage such as the Portal Network (opens in a new tab).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:blockchain-sharding/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Ethereum is a distributed network of computers (known as nodes) running software that can verify blocks and transaction data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The software must be run on your computer to turn it into an Ethereum node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] There are two separate pieces of software (known as 'clients') required to form a node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] You should understand the concept of a peer-to-peer network and the basics of the EVM before diving deeper and running your own instance of an Ethereum client.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Take a look at our introduction to Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] If you're new to the topic of nodes, we recommend first checking out our user-friendly introduction on running an Ethereum node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] A "node" is any instance of Ethereum client software that is connected to other computers also running Ethereum software, forming a network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] A client is an implementation of Ethereum that verifies data against the protocol rules and keeps the network secure.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] A node has to run two clients: a consensus client and an execution client.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] These clients work together to keep track of the head of the Ethereum chain and allow users to interact with the Ethereum network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The modular design with multiple pieces of software working together is called encapsulated complexity (opens in a new tab).
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] This approach made it easier to execute The Merge seamlessly, makes client software easier to maintain and develop, and enables the reuse of individual clients, for example, in the layer 2 ecosystem.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] (Coupled execution and consensus clients) Simplified diagram of a coupled execution and consensus client.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Both execution clients and consensus clients exist in a variety of programming languages developed by different teams.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Multiple client implementations can make the network stronger by reducing its dependency on a single codebase.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The ideal goal is to achieve diversity without any client dominating the network, thereby eliminating a potential single point of failure.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The variety of languages also invites a broader developer community and allows them to create integrations in their preferred language.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] What these implementations have in common is they all follow a single specification.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Specifications dictate how the Ethereum network and blockchain functions.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Multiple trackers offer a real-time overview of nodes in the Ethereum network.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Note that due to the nature of decentralized networks, these crawlers can only provide a limited view of the network and might report different results.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] If you want to run your own node, you should understand that there are different types of node that consume data differently.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] In fact, clients can run three different types of nodes: light, full and archive.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] There are also options of different sync strategies which enable faster synchronization time.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Synchronization refers to how quickly it can get the most up-to-date information on Ethereum's state.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Full nodes do a block-by-block validation of the blockchain, including downloading and verifying the block body and state data for each block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] There are different classes of full node - some start from the genesis block and verify every single block in the entire history of the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Others start their verification at a more recent block that they trust to be valid (e.g., Geth's 'snap sync').
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Regardless of where the verification starts, full nodes only keep a local copy of relatively recent data (typically the most recent 128 blocks), allowing older data to be deleted to save disk space.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Older data can be regenerated when it is needed.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Archive nodes are full nodes that verify every block from genesis and never delete any of the downloaded data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Syncing clients in any mode other than archive will result in pruned blockchain data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] This means, there is no archive of all historical states but the full node is able to build them on demand.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Instead of downloading every block, light nodes only download block headers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] These headers contain summary information about the contents of the blocks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Any other information the light node requires gets requested from a full node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The light node can then independently verify the data they receive against the state roots in the block headers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Light nodes enable users to participate in the Ethereum network without the powerful hardware or high bandwidth required to run full nodes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Eventually, light nodes might run on mobile phones or embedded devices.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The light nodes do not participate in consensus (i.e., they cannot be validators), but they can access the Ethereum blockchain with the same functionality and security guarantees as a full node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Light clients are an area of active development for Ethereum and we expect to see new light clients for the consensus layer and execution layer soon.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] There are also potential routes to providing light client data over the gossip network (opens in a new tab).
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] This is advantageous because the gossip network could support a network of light nodes without requiring full nodes to serve requests.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Ethereum does not support a large population of light nodes yet, but light node support is an area expected to develop rapidly in the near future.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] In particular, clients like Nimbus (opens in a new tab), Helios (opens in a new tab), and LodeStar (opens in a new tab) are currently heavily focused on light nodes.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Running a node allows you to directly, trustlessly and privately use Ethereum while supporting the network by keeping it more robust and decentralized.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Running your own node enables you to use Ethereum in a private, self-sufficient and trustless manner.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] You don't need to trust the network because you can verify the data yourself with your client.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] "Don't trust, verify" is a popular blockchain mantra.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] A diverse set of nodes is important for Ethereum’s health, security and operational resiliency.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] If you run a full node, the whole Ethereum network benefits from it, even if you don't run a validator.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Interested in running your own Ethereum client?
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] For a beginner-friendly introduction visit our run a node page to learn more.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] If you're more of a technical user, dive into more details and options on how to spin up your own node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Setting up your own node can cost you time and resources but you don’t always need to run your own instance.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] In this case, you can use a third party API provider.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] For an overview of using these services, check out nodes as a service.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] If somebody runs an Ethereum node with a public API in your community, you can point your wallets to a community node via Custom RPC and gain more privacy than with some random trusted third party.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] On the other hand, if you run a client, you can share it with your friends who might need it.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The Ethereum community maintains multiple open-source execution clients (previously known as 'Eth1 clients', or just 'Ethereum clients'), developed by different teams using different programming languages.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] This makes the network stronger and more diverse.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The ideal goal is to achieve diversity without any client dominating to reduce any single points of failure.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] This table summarizes the different clients.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] All of them pass client tests (opens in a new tab) and are actively maintained to stay updated with network upgrades.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] For more on supported networks, read up on Ethereum networks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Each client has unique use cases and advantages, so you should choose one based on your own preferences.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Diversity allows implementations to be focused on different features and user audiences.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] You may want to choose a client based on features, support, programming language, or licences.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Hyperledger Besu is an enterprise-grade Ethereum client for public and permissioned networks.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It runs all of the Ethereum Mainnet features, from tracing to GraphQL, has extensive monitoring and is supported by ConsenSys, both in open community channels and through commercial SLAs for enterprises.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It is written in Java and is Apache 2.0 licensed.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Besu's extensive documentation (opens in a new tab) will guide you through all details on its features and setups.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Erigon, formerly known as Turbo‐Geth, started as a fork of Go Ethereum oriented toward speed and disk‐space efficiency.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Erigon is a completely re-architected implementation of Ethereum, currently written in Go but with implementations in other languages under development.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Erigon's goal is to provide a faster, more modular, and more optimized implementation of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It can perform a full archive node sync using around 2TB of disk space, in under 3 days.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Go Ethereum (Geth for short) is one of the original implementations of the Ethereum protocol.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Currently, it is the most widespread client with the biggest user base and variety of tooling for users and developers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It is written in Go, fully open source and licensed under the GNU LGPL v3.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Learn more about Geth in its documentation (opens in a new tab).
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Nethermind is an Ethereum implementation created with the C# .NET tech stack, licensed with LGPL-3.0, running on all major platforms including ARM.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Nethermind also has detailed documentation (opens in a new tab), strong dev support, an online community and 24/7 support available for premium users.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Reth (short for Rust Ethereum) is an Ethereum full node implementation that is focused on being user-friendly, highly modular, fast and efficient.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Reth was originally built and driven forward by Paradigm, and is licensed under the Apache and MIT licenses.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Reth is production ready, and suitable for usage in mission-critical environments such as staking or high-uptime services.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Performs well in use cases where high performance with great margins is required such as RPC, MEV, indexing, simulations, and P2P activities.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Learn more by checking out the Reth Book (opens in a new tab), or the Reth GitHub repo (opens in a new tab).
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] These clients are still in earlier stages of development and are not yet recommended for production use.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] There are multiple consensus clients (previously known as 'Eth2' clients) to support the consensus upgrades.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] They are responsible for all consensus-related logic including the fork-choice algorithm, processing attestations and managing proof-of-stake rewards and penalties.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Lighthouse is a consensus client implementation written in Rust under the Apache-2.0 license.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It is maintained by Sigma Prime and has been stable and production-ready since Beacon Chain genesis.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It is relied upon by various enterprises, staking pools and individuals.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It aims to be secure, performant and interoperable in a wide range of environments, from desktop PCs to sophisticated automated deployments.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Lodestar is a production-ready consensus client implementation written in Typescript under the LGPL-3.0 license.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It is maintained by ChainSafe Systems and is the newest of the consensus clients for solo-stakers, developers and researchers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Lodestar consists of a beacon node and validator client powered by JavaScript implementations of Ethereum protocols.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Lodestar aims to improve Ethereum usability with light clients, expand accessibility to a larger group of developers and further contribute to ecosystem diversity.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Nimbus is a consensus client implementation written in Nim under the Apache-2.0 license.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It is a production-ready client in use by solo-stakers and staking pools.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Nimbus is designed for resource efficiency, making it easy to run on resource-restricted devices and enterprise infrastructure with equal ease, without compromising stability or reward performance.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] A lighter resource footprint means the client has a greater margin of safety when the network is under stress.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Prysm is a full-featured, open source consensus client written in Go under the GPL-3.0 license.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It features an optional webapp UI and prioritizes user experience, documentation, and configurability for both stake-at-home and institutional users.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Visit Prysm docs (opens in a new tab) to learn more.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Teku is one of the original Beacon Chain genesis clients.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Alongside the usual goals (security, robustness, stability, usability, performance), Teku specifically aims to comply fully with all the various consensus client standards.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Teku offers very flexible deployment options.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The beacon node and validator client can be run together as a single process, which is extremely convenient for solo stakers, or nodes can be run separately for sophisticated staking operations.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] In addition, Teku is fully interoperable with Web3Signer (opens in a new tab) for signing key security and slashing protection.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Teku is written in Java and is Apache 2.0 licensed.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It is developed by the Protocols team at ConsenSys that is also responsible for Besu and Web3Signer.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Learn more in Teku docs (opens in a new tab).
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Grandine is a consensus client implementation, written in Rust under the GPL-3.0 license.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It is maintained by the Grandine Core Team and is fast, high-performance and lightweight.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It fits a wide range of stakers from solo stakers running on low-resource devices such as Raspberry Pi to large institutional stakers running tens of thousands of validators.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] To follow and verify current data in the network, the Ethereum client needs to sync with the latest network state.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] This is done by downloading data from peers, cryptographically verifying their integrity, and building a local blockchain database.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Synchronization modes represent different approaches to this process with various trade-offs.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Clients also vary in their implementation of sync algorithms.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Always refer to the official documentation of your chosen client for specifics on implementation.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The execution layer may be run in different modes to suit different use cases, from re-executing the blockchain's world state to only syncing with the tip of the chain from a trusted checkpoint.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] A full sync downloads all blocks (including headers and block bodies) and regenerates the state of the blockchain incrementally by executing every block from genesis.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Archive nodes perform a full sync to build (and retain) a complete history of the state changes made by every transaction in every block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Like a full sync, a fast sync downloads all blocks (including headers, transactions, and receipts).
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] However, instead of re-processing the historical transactions, a fast sync relies on the receipts until it reaches a recent head, when it switches to importing and processing blocks to provide a full node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Snap syncs also verify the chain block-by-block.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] However, instead of starting at the genesis block, a snap sync starts at a more recent 'trusted' checkpoint that is known to be part of the true blockchain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The node saves periodic checkpoints while deleting data older than a certain age.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] These snapshots are used to regenerate state data as needed, rather than storing it forever.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Light client mode downloads all block headers, block data, and verifies some randomly.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Only syncs tip of the chain from the trusted checkpoint.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Optimistic sync is a post-merge synchronization strategy designed to be opt-in and backwards compatible, allowing execution nodes to sync via established methods.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The execution engine can *optimistically* import beacon blocks without fully verifying them, find the latest head, and then start syncing the chain with the above methods.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Then, after the execution client has caught up, it will inform the consensus client of the validity of the transactions in the Beacon Chain.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] A checkpoint sync, also known as weak subjectivity sync, creates a superior user experience for syncing a Beacon Node.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] It's based on assumptions of weak subjectivity which enables syncing the Beacon Chain from a recent weak subjectivity checkpoint instead of genesis.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] Checkpoint syncs make the initial sync time significantly faster with similar trust assumptions as syncing from .
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] In practice, this means your node connects to a remote service to download recent finalized states and continues verifying data from that point.
[src:blockchain-sharding/nodes-and-clients] The third party providing the data is trusted and should be picked carefully.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] A **database shard**, or simply a **shard**, is a horizontal partition of data within a database or search engine.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Each shard may be held on a separate database server instance in order to spread across multiple servers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Some data in a database may remain present in all shards, while other data is stored in only one shard.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] In such cases, each shard acts as the single source for its subset of data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] There are numerous advantages to the horizontal partitioning of data.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Since tables are divided and distributed into multiple servers, the total number of rows in each table in each database is reduced.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This reduces index size, which generally improves search performance.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] A database shard can be placed on separate hardware, and multiple shards can be placed on multiple machines.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This enables the distribution of a database across a large number of machines, which can significantly improve performance.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] In addition, if the database shard is based on some real-world segmentation of the data (e.g., European customers v.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] American customers) it may be possible to infer the appropriate shard membership easily and automatically, and to query only the relevant shard.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Although it has long been implemented through manual coding (especially where rows have an obvious grouping, as in the customer region example above), this approach is often inflexible.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] There is a desire to support sharding automatically, both in terms of adding code support for it, and for identifying candidates to be sharded separately.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Consistent hashing is a technique used in sharding to distribute large loads across multiple smaller services and servers.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Where distributed computing is used to separate load between multiple servers (either for performance or reliability reasons), a sharding approach may also be useful.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] In the 2010s, sharding of execution capacity, as well as the more traditional sharding of data, emerged as a potential approach to address performance and scalability challenges in blockchains.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Recent academic work has proposed protocols such as Cerberus to address cross-shard atomicity by braiding consensus across multiple shards, allowing transactions to affect multiple partitions simultaneously without requiring a global lock.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Horizontal partitioning splits one or more tables by row, usually within a *single* instance of a schema and a database server.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] It partitions the relevant table or tables in the same way, but does so across potentially *multiple* instances of the schema.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] An advantage is that the search load for the large partitioned table can be distributed across multiple servers (logical or physical), rather than only across multiple indexes on a same logical server.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Splitting shards across multiple isolated instances requires more than simple horizontal partitioning.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] The expected gains in efficiency would be reduced if querying the database required *multiple* instances to be accessed just to retrieve a simple dimension table.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Beyond partitioning, sharding therefore involves distributing large, partitionable tables across servers, while smaller tables are replicated in full on each server.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This is also why sharding is related to a shared-nothing architecture—once sharded, each shard can reside in a separate logical schema instance, physical database server, data center, or geographic region.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Sharding is intended to minimize the need for cross-shard access by partitioning data across independent shards.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This makes replication across multiple servers easier (simple horizontal partitioning does not).
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] It is also useful for worldwide distribution of applications, where communications links between data centers might otherwise become a bottleneck.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] There is also a requirement for some notification and replication mechanism between schema instances, so that unpartitioned tables remain as closely synchronized as the application requires.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] This is a complex architectural choice in sharded systems: approaches range from making these tables effectively read-only (with updates that are rare and batched), to dynamically replicated tables (at the cost of reducing some of the distribution benefits of sharding), and many options in between.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Sharding a database table before it has been optimized locally can introduce unnecessary complexity.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Sharding is generally recommended when other optimization strategies have proven insufficient.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] The added complexity of database sharding can result in several potential challenges.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Richard Garriott, creator of *Ultima Online*, recalled that the term originated during the production of the game, specifically in creating a self-regulating, virtual ecology system.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] Players were able to interact and harvest in-game resources via the internet, which disrupted the balance of the system.
[src:blockchain-sharding/shard-database-architecture] The feature was later removed after several months of testing.
